","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","Gwlad Morgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"about 1380–":"about 1380–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","about 1380":"about 1380","1400":"1400","1342":"1342","about 1400":"about 1400","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","Gwlad Morgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bach","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Zachary  , also used as an independent given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Zachary","meanings":["vernacular form of the New Testament Greek name <i>Zacharias</i>, a form of Hebrew   Zechariah   ‘God has remembered’. This was the name of the father of John the Baptist, who underwent a temporary period of dumbness for his lack of faith (Luke 1), and of a more obscure figure, Zacharias son of Barachias, who was slain ‘between the temple and the altar’ (Matthew 23:35; Luke 11:51). In the United States it is familiar as the name of a 19th-century president,  Zachary Taylor . Since the 1990s the name has been remarkably popular in the English-speaking world, especially in the United States."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Bach was born about 1380, in Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Griffith Goch, was 42 and his mother, Mrs. Griffith Goch, was 39. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs. David Bach."},"et":{"about 1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1400":"1400","1342":"1342","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","Gwlad Morgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1380–":"noin 1380–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1342–Female":"1342–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","1400":"1400","1342":"1342","about 1400":"noin 1400","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","Gwlad Morgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1380–":"environ 1380–Décédé","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1342–Female":"1342–Décédée","about 1380":"environ 1380","1400":"1400","1342":"1342","about 1400":"environ 1400","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","Gwlad Morg